rio developed television shows for [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and [[NBC]] and were chosen three times to perform at the [[Aspen Comedy Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nash with Upright Citizens Brigade|url=http://www.cc.com/shows/upright-citizens-brigade|publisher=Comedy Central}}</ref>\n\nNash wrote, directed and starred in his [[Comedy Central]] web series \"Jason Nash Is Married\", which was based on his one-man show \"In the Land of Tall Buildings and Red Fire Engines\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-jason-nash-is-married-review-20140905-story.html|title=Fun 'Jason Nash Is Married' explores love and showbiz|last=Goldstein|first=Gary|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> A film version of \"Jason Nash Is Married\" was released in 2014 starring [[Busy Philipps]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Nash|first=Jason|title=Jason Nash Is Married|date=2014-06-24|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3737782/|others=Jason Nash, Busy Philipps, Casey Wilson|accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref> Nash also created the web series \"How to Be a Man and The Shaman\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelaughbutton.com/interviews/jason-nash-says-fml-new-indie-comedy/|title=Jason Nash says \"FML\" in his new indie comedy -|website=thelaughbutton.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> In 2016, Nash starred and directed his own screenplay, a road trip comedy film \"FML\" featuring fellow Vine star Brandon Calvillo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/jason-nash-brandon-calvillo-fml-vine-1201743390/|title=Vine Stars Jason Nash, Brandon Calvillo Join Road Trip Comedy \u2018FML\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=2016-03-31|work=Variety|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nNash co-created the long-running podcast \"Guys with Feelings\" which debuted in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jason Nash, a Guy with Feelings|url=http://laist.com/2008/12/11/interview_jason_nash.php|publisher=laist.com|accessdate=11 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081214135920/http://laist.com/2008/12/11/interview_jason_nash.php|archivedate=14 December 2008}}</ref> He has developed shows for Fox, NBC,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0621738/|title=Jason Nash|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> [[CBS]], [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]] and IFC. He has also acted in various shows including an opening of ''[[House MD]]'' episode 'The Tyrant', ''[[The Simpsons]]'' and ''[[Drake & Josh]].''  Nash is currently a YouTube [[vlogger]], and has over 2.5 million subscribers on his main channel.<ref>U. (n.d.). JasonNashComedy YouTube Stats, Channel Statistics. Retrieved from https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/jasonnashcomedy</ref> Nash became a Youtube Vlogger after being discovered by fellow Viner, [[David Dobrik & \"The Vlog Squad\"|David Dobrik]], one night at a comedy club. He began his Youtube career as a character in David Dobrik's vlogs, and soon began to upload his own videos. His first video was uploaded on December 2, 2016.<ref>Nash, J. (2016, December 02). Retrieved November 01, 2018, from https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ubgAC-5wF2A</ref>\n\nNash also runs a weekly podcast named \"Views\" with fellow YouTube personality David Dobrik. During its debut in 2017, \"Views\" climbed to #3 on the iTunes charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/10th/jasonnash|title=Jason Nash - The Shorty Awards|website=shortyawards.com|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref>  Jason Nash and David Dobrik also took their podcast on a live tour across the US in summer of 2018, with their fellow youtube friends, called the \"Vlog Squad\".<ref>VIEWS SUMMER TOUR 2018. (n.d.). Retrieved from http://viewstour.com/</ref> They called it the \"VIEWS\" Tour. This included performances from other Youtubers such as Scotty Sire, live stories and a live Q&A session.<ref>Weiss, G. (2018, May 15). Vlogger/Podcasters David Dobrik And Jason Nash To Kick Off Summer Tour. Retrieved from https://www.tubefilter.com/2018/05/15/david-dobrik-and-jason-nash-views-tour/</ref>  Nash has stated that he is focused on Youtube as his career and because of this he uploads multiple times a week. For approximately one year, Nash had a second channel titled \"Jason Nash Family\" dedicated to his life with his children, Charley and Wyatt.<ref>(n.d.). Retrieved November 01, 2018, from https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCWcVikU5Sv-AqMtjV-BVsLQ</ref> This channel was later shut down by the request of his ex-wife Marney, who requested that the children would not be on the internet in such a drastic way. Because of this, Nash has put all his attention to his main Youtube channel.\n\n==Personal life==\nNash graduated from [[Medfield High School]] in 1991 and then attended college at the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]. After he left college, he worked as an assistant to [[Norm Macdonald]] on  ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''. Nash moved to Hollywood in 2001 when he was cast on the sketch show Random Play for [[VH1]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.laweekly.com/arts/how-jason-nash-makes-a-living-in-web-series-4254799|title=How Jason Nash Makes a Living in Web Series|last=Carrie|first=Stephanie|date=2014-02-18|work=L.A. Weekly|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref>\n\nHe was in a relationship with fellow Youtuber [[Trisha Paytas]]. The couple began dating in 2018, but were reported to have separated in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Newsweek]]|url=https://www.newsweek.com/trisha-paytas-david-dobrik-twitter-jason-nash-1317335|title=YouTuber Trisha Paytas Calls Out David Dobrik and Vlog Squad for Manipulation|date=February 4, 2019|author=Asarch, Steven|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190527031338/https://www.newsweek.com/trisha-paytas-david-dobrik-twitter-jason-nash-1317335|archive-date=May 27, 2019|access-date=August 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2019, fellow YouTuber [[David Dobrik]] legally married Lorraine Nash, Nash's mother, as a [[Sketch comedy|bit]] for one of his vlogs. On June 12, 2019, Dobrik announced that he and Lorraine had decided to end their marriage after one month. On November 22, 2019, Dobrik stated via Instagram that he has officially signed divorce papers and divorced Nash.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Television and film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Drake & Josh]]''\n| Waiter\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[House (TV series)|House]]''\n| Neighbor\n|\n|-\n|2007\u20132010\n|''[[SuperNews!]]''\n| Multiple Characters \n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''Jason Nash is Married''\n| Jason Nash\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[The Simpsons]]''\n| Southie Criminals / Philantrophic Southies \n| Season 28, Episode 3: \"[[The Town (The Simpsons)|The Town]]\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/JasonNashComedy Jason Nash Comedy YouTube Channel]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nash, Jason}}\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Boston]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Vine celebrities]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n", "name_user": "72.230.183.138", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jason_Nash"}
{"title_page": "Glendale Community College (California)", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Glendale University College of Law}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2013}}\n{{cleanup|date=April 2015|reason=formatting}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Glendale Community College\n| motto = How Do You GCC?<ref name=GCCmotto>\"The tagline 'How Do You GCC?' was developed to provoke a response from the audience. It asks the individual to think about their relationship with the college. This applies to students, members of the faculty and staff, community members and anyone that has interaction with Glendale Community College.\" {{cite web|url=https://www.glendale.edu/about-gcc/communications/style-guide/logo|title=Style Guide - Logo|work=Glendale Community College|accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>\n| established = 1927\n| type = [[Community colleges in the United States|Community College]]\n| endowment = $14,586,000 (2019)<ref name=GCCendowment>Note 7 - Donor Designated Endowments. {{cite web|url=http://www.glendale.edu/about-gcc/foundation-community/financial-data |title=Glendale College Foundation Audit Report|work=Glendale College Foundation, Inc. (A California Nonprofit Corporation)|date= June 30, 2014|accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| president = Dr. David Viar<ref name=GCCpresident>{{cite web|url=http://www.glendale.edu/about-gcc/administration|title=About GCC: Administration|work=Glendale Community College|accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| city = [[Glendale, California|Glendale]]\n| state = [[California]]\n| country = [[United States]]\n| athletics = [[California Community College Athletic Association|CCCAA]] \u2013 [[Western State Conference|WSC]],<br> SCFA (football)\n| nickname = Vaqueros<ref name=GCCathletics>{{cite web|url=http://www.glendale.edu/?page=3608|title=Glendale College Athletics|work=Glendale Community College|accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| colors = Cardinal & Gold {{color box|#a6093d}} {{color box|#eaaa00}}<ref name=GCCcolors>\"The official colors of Glendale College are cardinal and gold ...\" {{cite web|url=http://www.glendale.edu/about-gcc/public-information/style-guide/fonts-colors|title=About GCC: Style Guide - Fonts & Colors|work=Glendale Community College|accessdate=October 11, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225052035/http://www.glendale.edu/about-gcc/public-information/style-guide/fonts-colors|archive-date=February 25, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|http://www.glendale.edu}}\n| parent = [[California Community Colleges System]]\n| students = 19,207<ref name=GCCstudents>{{cite web|url=http://datamart.cccco.edu/Students/Enrollment_Status.aspx|title=Enrollment Status Summary|work=California Community Colleges Chancellor's Office|accessdate=October 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| superintendent = Dr. David Viar<ref name=GCCpresident/>\n| image = Glendale_Community_College_CA_logo.png\n}}\n[[Image:Glendale College.jpg|thumb|Four boys for every girl at Glendale College, 1948]]\n[[Image:GCC bro.jpg|thumb|The John A. Davitt Administration building]]\n'''Glendale Community College''' ('''GCC''') is a [[community college]] in [[Glendale, California|Glendale]], [[California]].\n\n== History ==\nThe college was founded as '''Glendale Junior College''' in 1927, to serve the Glendale Union High School District which at the time included [[La Crescenta-Montrose, California|La Crescenta]], [[Glendale, California|Glendale]], and [[Sunland-Tujunga, Los Angeles|Tujunga]]. From 1927 to 1929 classes were held in the buildings of Glendale Union High School at Broadway and Verdugo in the City of Glendale. In 1929 the junior college moved to the Harvard School plant of the Glendale Union High School District where it remained until 1937. In this year a new plant, part of the present one, was completed and occupied. The year before, in 1936, the Glendale Junior College District was dissolved as such and became a part of the new Glendale Unified School District. The name of the school was changed to '''Glendale College''' in 1944. On July 1, 1970 Glendale College became a part of the Glendale Junior College District. On April 20, 1971 the Board of Education adopted a resolution changing the District name to Glendale Community College District.\n\nOn November 3, 1980, Glendale voters approved a measure to establish separate Boards, with the new board taking office in April 1981. The separation resulted in the creation of a Board of Trustees solely responsible for the governance of the Glendale Community College District. In 1936, {{convert|25|acre|ha}} were acquired for the present site of the college. \n\nGlendale Community College inspired the NBC show ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' which premiered in the fall season of 2009. The show uses the fictional setting of Greendale Community College; the show's creator, [[Dan Harmon]], has stated that the show was actually based on his experience attending Glendale Community College. Harmon describes the series as \"flawed characters [coming into Greendale] and becoming unflawed by being in this place because it's been underestimated by the system around it.\"<ref name=leland_autobio>[http://www.dailynews.com/news/ci_13357418/ \"Glendale Community College inspired NBC show airing tonight\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603233757/http://www.dailynews.com/news/ci_13357418/ |date=2011-06-03 }} Los Angeles Daily News 17 September 2009</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\nThe campus now consists of {{convert|100|acre|ha}} and 15 permanent buildings. It is located on the slopes of the San Rafael Hills overlooking the valleys in the Glendale area.\n\n== Organization and administration ==\nThe college president is Dr. David Viar.\n\n===Glendale Community College District===\nThe Glendale Community College District is a constituent [[community college]] district of the [[California Community College System]] (CCCS), whose only college is GCC.\n\nIt is governed by a 5-member elected Board of Trustees, elected by geographical district effective in 2017. Pursuant to their authority, they have promulgated policies and administrative regulations for the administration of the district and GCC and serves Glendale and [[La Crescenta-Montrose, California|La Crescenta-Montrose]]. \n\nThe elections for the Glendale Community College Board of Trustees is held at the same day the Glendale City Council and Glendale Unified School District Board of Education, which takes place on a first Tuesday after the first Monday in April of odd-numbered years. Effective with the March 2020 election, the elections are held on a first Tuesday after the first Monday.\n\n===Accreditation===\nGlendale Community College was evaluated in 2010 by the Accrediting Commission for Community and Junior Colleges Western Association of Schools and Colleges and is an\naccredited institution.  The next regular evaluation was to be in 2016.[http://www.glendale.edu/home/showdocument?id=19260 ACCJC Action Letter - July 3, 2013]\n[http://www.glendale.edu/accreditation]\n\n== Academic profile ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; float:right; font-size:85%; margin-left:2em; margin:auto;\"\n|+ ''Fall 2017 Demographics of student body''<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 USNEWS: Glendale Community College Overview|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/community-colleges/glendale-community-college-CC03222}}</ref>\n|-\n! [[Hispanic and Latino American]]\n| 32%\n|-\n! [[African American]]\n| 2%\n|-\n! [[Asian American]]\n| 8%\n|-\n! [[Native Hawaiian]] or other [[Pacific Islander]]\n| 0%\n|-\n! [[European Americans|White European Americans]]\n| 48%\n|-\n! [[Multiracial Americans]]\n| 3%\n|-\n! [[International students]]\n| 5%\n|-\n! Unknown\n| 2%\n|-\n! [[Female]]\n| 55%\n|-\n| [[Male]]\n| 45%\n|-  \n|}\n\nThe in-state tuition and fees for 2017-2018 were $1,175, and out-of-state tuition and fees were $6,335. The student-faculty ratio is 26-to-1. There is no application fee. Total enrollment of 14,598 as of fall 2017. Full-time 6,634 and part-time 7,964 students. More than 15,000 students enroll in credit courses and over 7,000 more enroll in non-credit courses. The school has an open admissions policy and offers credit for life experiences.\n\n== Athletics ==\nThe college athletic teams are nicknamed the Vaqueros (men) or Lady Vaqueros (women). Glendale currently fields eight men\u2019s and eight women\u2019s varsity teams. It competes as a member of the [[California Community College Athletic Association]] (CCCAA) in the [[Western State Conference]] (WSC) for all sports except football, which competes in [[Southern California Football Association]] (SCFA).<ref>{{cite web |title=2019-20 CCCAA Directory |url=https://cccaa.prestosports.com/about/directory/2019-20/Directory040620.pdf |publisher=California Community College Athletic Association |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n== Notable people ==\n=== Alumni ===\n{{main list|:Category:Glendale Community College (California) alumni}}\n*[[Mark Caguioa]], professional basketball player \n*[[Glenn Corbett]], actor\n*[[Marian Cleeves Diamond]], Professor Emeritus of Anatomy & Neuroanatomy at University of California, Berkeley, taught at UCB for over 50 years; one of the founders of modern neuroscience\n*[[Angie Dickinson]], actress\n*[[Marco Estrada (baseball)|Marco Estrada]], pitcher Toronto Blue Jays\n*[[Cathy Ferguson]], two-time Olympic gold medalist swimmer\n*[[Bob Gagliano]], American football player\n*[[Blake Gailen]] (born 1985), American-Israeli baseball player\n*[[Beverly Garland]], actress\n*[[Dan Harmon]], television writer/producer, creator of ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'', Rick and Morty.\n*[[Ron Lopez]], football player\n*[[Hue Jackson]], NFL coach\n*[[Donald D. Lorenzen]] (1920\u201380), LA City Council member, 1969\u201377\n*[[Masiela Lusha]], actress\n*[[Eva Mendes]], actress\n* [[Dick Moje]], [[National Football League]] player<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=MOJEDIC01|title= Dick Moje|publisher= database Football.com|accessdate= November 26, 2012|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120530121017/http://databasefootball.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=MOJEDIC01|archivedate= May 30, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Ricky Ortiz]], professional wrestler\n*[[Danielle Panabaker]], actress\n*[[Kay Panabaker]], actress\n*[[Andy Reid]], NFL coach\n*[[Freddy Sanchez]], baseball player\n*[[Seann William Scott]], actor\n*[[Ryan Seacrest]], broadcaster, producer\n*[[Schoolboy Q]], rapper\n*[[Ryan Sherriff]] (born 1990), Major League baseball player for the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]\n*[[Lon Simmons]], broadcaster\n*[[Juno Stover-Irwin|Juno Stover]], two-time Olympic diving medalist; two-time USA-[[Amateur Athletic Union|AAU]] champion; two-time [[Pan-American Games]] medalist\n*[[Vic Tayback]], actor\n*[[Erick Thohir]], Indonesian businessman\n*[[Jordi Vilasuso]], actor\n*[[Kyle Vincent]], musician\n*[[Frank Wykoff]], three-time Olympic gold medalist runner\n*[[Pablo Calamera]], Silicon Valley technologist/entrepreneur\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.glendale.edu Official website]\n\n{{Glendale, California}}\n{{Western State Conference}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Los Angeles County}}\n{{California Community College System}}\n\n{{Coord|34|10|01.99|N|118|13|42.17|W|format=dms|display=title|type:edu_region:US-CA}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Glendale Community College (California)| ]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Glendale, California]]\n[[Category:California Community Colleges System]]\n[[Category:Education in Glendale, California]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1927]]\n[[Category:Schools accredited by the Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Los Angeles County, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Glendale University College of Law}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2013}}\n{{cleanup|date=April 201